The Agricultural and Food Authority has opened an office in Maua town, Meru. The office is part of the national government’s plan to make miraa a mainstream cash crop. The office is also meant to improve farmers’ welfare. The office is part of the national government’s plan to make miraa a mainstream cash crop. Major European markets banned miraa sales, saying it is a stimulant. Agriculture CS Willy Bett said the national government has partnered with Meru county to support the miraa industry since it was classified as a cash crop. The CS’s speech was read by Andrew Osondo from the ministry during the opening of the office on Saturday. “In partnership with the county government the authority needs to come up with strategies to eradicate the challenges facing the miraa sector by considering multiple income generating methods,” Bett said.